Project: Identify Customer Segments¶

In this project, you will apply unsupervised learning techniques to identify segments of the population that form the core customer base for a mail-order sales company in Germany. These segments can then be used to direct marketing campaigns towards audiences that will have the highest expected rate of returns. The data that you will use has been provided by our partners at Bertelsmann Arvato Analytics, and represents a real-life data science task.

This notebook will help you complete this task by providing a framework within which you will perform your analysis steps. In each step of the project, you will see some text describing the subtask that you will perform, followed by one or more code cells for you to complete your work. Feel free to add additional code and markdown cells as you go along so that you can explore everything in precise chunks. The code cells provided in the base template will outline only the major tasks, and will usually not be enough to cover all of the minor tasks that comprise it.

It should be noted that while there will be precise guidelines on how you should handle certain tasks in the project, there will also be places where an exact specification is not provided. Step 0: Load the Data¶

There are four files associated with this project (not including this one):

  • Udacity_AZDIAS_Subset.csv: Demographics data for the general population of Germany; 891211 persons (rows) x 85 features (columns).
  • Udacity_CUSTOMERS_Subset.csv: Demographics data for customers of a mail-order company; 191652 persons (rows) x 85 features (columns).
  • Data_Dictionary.md: Detailed information file about the features in the provided datasets.
  • AZDIAS_Feature_Summary.csv: Summary of feature attributes for demographics data; 85 features (rows) x 4 columns

Each row of the demographics files represents:

  • a single person,
  • but also includes information outside of individuals, including information about their household, building, and neighborhood.
  1. You will use this information to cluster the general population into groups with similar demographic properties.
  2. Then, you will see how the people in the customers dataset fit into those created clusters. The hope here is that certain clusters are over-represented in the customers data, as compared to the general population; those over-represented clusters will be assumed to be part of the core userbase. This information can then be used for further applications, such as targeting for a marketing campaign.

To start off with, load in the demographics data for the general population into a pandas DataFrame, and do the same for the feature attributes summary. Note for all of the .csv data files in this project: they're semicolon (;) delimited, so you'll need an additional argument in your read_csv() call to read in the data properly. Also, considering the size of the main dataset, it may take some time for it to load completely.

Once the dataset is loaded, it's recommended that you take a little bit of time just browsing the general structure of the dataset and feature summary file. You'll be getting deep into the innards of the cleaning in the first major step of the project, so gaining some general familiarity can help you get your bearings.

Summary of specific dataset feature groupings¶

The dataset labels aren't very readable by first glance, going through the 85 features, here is a summary by groupings

  1. Person - age/DOB , gender, purchasing information sources & habits, vacation habits, personal financial standing, health status, detailed and higher level life stage/family information, social status, academic background, nationality, politics
  2. Household - Age of household and length of residence, people in household, household income
  3. Building - Type of building, households in building, location of building (East / West germany), neighborhood quality
  4. RR4 microcell - lifestage information of microcell
  5. RR3 microcell - buildings in microcell, households in microcell
  6. Macrocell - buildings in macrocell, households in macrocell
  7. Postcode - distance to urban center, distance to city center, density of households
  8. Region - neighborhood type (e.g. upper/middle class etc), purchasing power, online affinity
  9. Community - unemployment data and size of community

From the summary above, majority of the data are factual data which is always beneficial for data modelling. One non-factual data found is W_KEIT_KIND_HH - Likelihood of children in household.

Data types¶

  • Only 8% of our data is numeric, while the remainder are categorical (in the sense that they are quantitative variables, not to be confused with the categorical labelling for 1 data type below), and a single time-series data.

Numeric data

  • Most of numerical features make sense
  • Considerations would be to update the following to datetime features:
    1. GEBURTSJAHR - Year of birth
    2. MIN_GEBAEUDEJAHR - First year building was mentioned in the database

Timeseries/Datetime data

  • The only timeseries, ALTER_HH - birthdate of head of household is appropriate to be datetime

Categorical

  • From now onwards, we would be using the terms nominal and ordinal to describe the 2 types of categorical variables. Nominal categories do not have an intrinsic ordering. E.g. Primary 2 genders would be male and female. Ordinal categories would have an ordering towards them. E.g. would be the REGIOTYP feature (describing neighborhood typology) where a 1 score would relate to individuals in upper-class while a lower score of 4 is middle-class and 7 is marginal groups.
    • Ordinal - Inspection of ordinal variables below suggest that they are appropriate
    • Nominal - Similarly, inspection of them suggest that they are appropriate
  • There is also an additional category mixed where it contains a mix of ordinal and nominal labellings. Take PLZ8_BAUMAX for example (describing most common building type in region), there is ordinal quality where numbers 1 to 4 is a scale of number of family homes. However, label 5 would be used to describe that the area mainly relates to business buildings.
    • It may be beneficial to create a new feature set to segregate these mixed variables, e.g. for the case above we could have another feature column containing boolean on whether the area primarily has to residential or business buildings.
    • However, not all features in the Mixed columns are this straightforward

Step 1.1.1: Convert Missing Value Codes to NaNs¶

The fourth column of the feature attributes summary (loaded in above as feat_info) documents the codes from the data dictionary that indicate missing or unknown data. While the file encodes this as a list (e.g. [-1,0]), this will get read in as a string object. You'll need to do a little bit of parsing to make use of it to identify and clean the data. Convert data that matches a 'missing' or 'unknown' value code into a numpy NaN value. You might want to see how much data takes on a 'missing' or 'unknown' code, and how much data is naturally missing, as a point of interest.

As one more reminder, you are encouraged to add additional cells to break up your analysis into manageable chunks.

In [17]:
# Identify missing or unknown data values and convert them to NaNs.
# Note: There is an issue with matplotlib where the label axis is alphabetically ordered
# - https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49647875/how-to-prevent-alphabetical-sorting-for-python-bars-with-matplotlib
def get_null(df):
    null = (df.shape[0] - df.describe().loc['count'])
    null.sort_values(ascending=False, inplace=True)
    return null

def plot_null(null, title, w, h):
    plt.figure(figsize=(w, h))
    null.plot.barh()
    plt.xlabel('Number of missing data')
    plt.ylabel('Features')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show()

def make_list(elem):
    # https://stackoverflow.com/questions/23119472/in-pandas-python-reading-array-stored-as-string
    elem = elem[1:-1].split(',')
    # Strip negative sign - https://stackoverflow.com/questions/28279732/how-to-type-negative-number-with-isdigit
    for i in range(len(elem)):
        if elem[i].lstrip('-').isnumeric():
            elem[i] = int(elem[i])
    return elem

missing_unknown = [make_list(x) for x in feat_info['missing_or_unknown']]
In [22]:
# Converting string to array
def df_make_na(df):
    new_df = df.copy()
    for att, unknown in zip(feat_info['attribute'], missing_unknown):
        new_df[att] = new_df[att].apply(lambda x : np.nan if x in unknown else x)
    return new_df

Step 1.1.3: Assess Missing Data in Each Row¶

Now, you'll perform a similar assessment for the rows of the dataset. How much data is missing in each row? As with the columns, you should see some groups of points that have a very different numbers of missing values. Divide the data into two subsets: one for data points that are above some threshold for missing values, and a second subset for points below that threshold.

In order to know what to do with the outlier rows, we should see if the distribution of data values on columns that are not missing data (or are missing very little data) are similar or different between the two groups. Select at least five of these columns and compare the distribution of values.

  • You can use seaborn's countplot() function to create a bar chart of code frequencies and matplotlib's subplot() function to put bar charts for the two subplots side by side.
  • To reduce repeated code, you might want to write a function that can perform this comparison, taking as one of its arguments a column to be compared.

Depending on what you observe in your comparison, this will have implications on how you approach your conclusions later in the analysis. If the distributions of non-missing features look similar between the data with many missing values and the data with few or no missing values, then we could argue that simply dropping those points from the analysis won't present a major issue. On the other hand, if the data with many missing values looks very different from the data with few or no missing values, then we should make a note on those data as special. We'll revisit these data later on. Either way, you should continue your analysis for now using just the subset of the data with few or no missing values.

Steps to tackle missing data¶

  1. Understanding distribution of missing data in terms of data observations / rows
  2. Quantify amount of missing data discarded if choose deletion strategy
  3. Analysis of observations for low/moderate missing data
  4. Analysis of feature distribution between:
    • 4.1. Zero missing data vs remainder with missing data
    • 4.2. Zero missing data / Low/moderate missing data

1. Understanding distribution of missing data in terms of data observations¶

  • No/Low missing data - From our histogram plot below, we can see majority of missing/unknown data is aggregated within the 0 to 5 range (i.e. having 0 to 5 missing columns)
  • High missing data - A clear distinction can be seen for missing data from 30 onwards, there are large clumps of observations with missing data in 35, 42/43 and 45
    • We perform an analysis over feature distribution between this group and the group with no/low missing data.
    • For the purpose of this project, we will be removing these observations from our modelling
  • Moderate missing data - Data with 5 to 34 missing features
    • We perform an analysis of types of features missing. For the purpose of this exercise, it may be more time efficient to exlcude these observations given the additional time feature cleaning/engineering
    • We then subsequently perform an analysis over data distribution of these moderately missing data against our data with low missing data.

2. Quantify amount of missing data discarded if choose deletion strategy¶

  • Deletion is usually not a good strategy due to loss of valuable information, the guideline is usually to delete if the proportion of missing values from our dataset is very small
  • However for the purpose of this exercise, deletion is beneficial as feature cleaning/engineering may consume alot of time
  • In the scree plot below, we see the first bar with almost 900k data, which immediately drops to 250k, this means that there are approximately 650k data with zero unknown/missing values.
  • As we have concluded that we will be excluding high missing data, the horizontal line in our scree plot explains the amount of observations relating to high missing data, which is approx 100k

Step 1.2: Select and Re-Encode Features¶

Checking for missing data isn't the only way in which you can prepare a dataset for analysis. Since the unsupervised learning techniques to be used will only work on data that is encoded numerically, you need to make a few encoding changes or additional assumptions to be able to make progress. In addition, while almost all of the values in the dataset are encoded using numbers, not all of them represent numeric values. Check the third column of the feature summary (feat_info) for a summary of types of measurement.

  • For numeric and interval data, these features can be kept without changes.
  • Most of the variables in the dataset are ordinal in nature. While ordinal values may technically be non-linear in spacing, make the simplifying assumption that the ordinal variables can be treated as being interval in nature (that is, kept without any changes).
  • Special handling may be necessary for the remaining two variable types: categorical, and 'mixed'.

In the first two parts of this sub-step, you will perform an investigation of the categorical and mixed-type features and make a decision on each of them, whether you will keep, drop, or re-encode each. Then, in the last part, you will create a new data frame with only the selected and engineered columns.

Data wrangling is often the trickiest part of the data analysis process, and there's a lot of it to be done here. But stick with it: once you're done with this step, you'll be ready to get to the machine learning parts of the project!

We drop features with high number of missing values¶

A. Spread of data¶

  • numeric data will remain as is, and will immediately proceed to feature scaling in the next step
  • After removing feature with high number of missing values, we still observe that ordinal features contribute to a large majority of our featureset
    • As mentioned above, we will make the simple assumption that orinal variables can be treated as being interval, so no further re-encoding or engineering will be performed over this type of data
  • categorical features can be sub-divided into the following, where different strategies will be employed over them:
    1. binary - i.e. just 2 labels
    2. low cardinality - low number of unique labels
    3. moderate/high cardinality, higher number of unique labels
  • mixed variables require additional considerations which are not clear cut, of which we will be revisiting subsequently

Step 1.2.1: Re-Encode Categorical Features¶

For categorical data, you would ordinarily need to encode the levels as dummy variables. Depending on the number of categories, perform one of the following:

  • For binary (two-level) categoricals that take numeric values, you can keep them without needing to do anything.
    • There is one binary variable that takes on non-numeric values. For this one, you need to re-encode the values as numbers or create a dummy variable.
  • For multi-level categoricals (three or more values), you can choose to encode the values using multiple dummy variables (e.g. via OneHotEncoder), or (to keep things straightforward) just drop them from the analysis. As always, document your choices in the Discussion section.

B. Strategy for categorical features¶

  1. General guidelines
    • binary - remain
    • low cardinality - to one hot encode
    • moderate and high cardinality - to remove
  2. Specific guidelines
    • remain for features which are somewhat_ordinal upon inspection of Data Dictionary
    • remove features which seem like duplicates
In [56]:
# Assess categorical variables: which are binary, which are multi-level, and
# which one needs to be re-encoded?

def filter_info_clean(type_name):
    return feat_info[(feat_info['attribute'].isin(zero_azdias.columns)) & (feat_info['type'] == type_name)]

somewhat_ordinal = ['LP_FAMILIE_FEIN', 'LP_STATUS_FEIN', 'CAMEO_DEUG_2015']
# LP_FAMILIE_GROB can be mapped to LP_FAMILIE_FEIN
# LP_STATUS_GROB can be mapped to LP_STATUS_FEIN
# GEBAEUDETYP - feature set already has feature describing this, i.e. GEBAEUDETYP_RASTER
to_remove = ['LP_FAMILIE_GROB', 'LP_STATUS_GROB', 'GEBAEUDETYP']

def bucket_categorical(elem):
    if elem == 2:
        return 'binary'
    elif elem <= 5:
        return 'low'
    elif elem <= 10:
        return 'moderate'
    return 'high'

def map_categorical_strategy(row):
    att = row['attribute']
    card = row['cardinality']
    if att in somewhat_ordinal or card == 'binary':
        return 'do nothing'
    elif att in to_remove or card in ['moderate', 'high']:
        return 'delete'
    elif card == 'low':
        return 'one-hot encode'
    return elem

Discussion 1.2.1: Re-Encode Categorical Features¶

  • An assessment was made based on the cardinality of the categorical features to determine if we were to:

    1. delete
    2. one-hot encode
    3. do nothing

  • Binary categorical features do not require further action, so no further action will be required

  • We only consider low cardinal value categorical features to one hot encode since it will take considerable time for our algorithms to run considering the size of our dataset, a cut-off of 5 is taken
  • Moderate or high cardinal features are removed due to the reason above
  • Further inspection has been made over the Data_Dictionary to confirm if there are repeating categorical features, of which we can remove one of them, there are also some features which seem somewhat ordinal in nature, so we will remain them as well.

Step 1.2.2: Engineer Mixed-Type Features¶

There are a handful of features that are marked as "mixed" in the feature summary that require special treatment in order to be included in the analysis. There are two in particular that deserve attention; the handling of the rest are up to your own choices:

  • "PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE" combines information on three dimensions: generation by decade, movement (mainstream vs. avantgarde), and nation (east vs. west). While there aren't enough levels to disentangle east from west, you should create two new variables to capture the other two dimensions: an interval-type variable for decade, and a binary variable for movement.
  • "CAMEO_INTL_2015" combines information on two axes: wealth and life stage. Break up the two-digit codes by their 'tens'-place and 'ones'-place digits into two new ordinal variables (which, for the purposes of this project, is equivalent to just treating them as their raw numeric values).
  • If you decide to keep or engineer new features around the other mixed-type features, make sure you note your steps in the Discussion section.

Be sure to check Data_Dictionary.md for the details needed to finish these tasks.

C. Strategy for Mixed features¶

  • Both LP_LEBENSPHASE_FEIN and LP_LEBENSPHASE_GROB are related to each other
    • they both relate to life stages
    • Unfortunately they do not have a direct ordinal quality in them
    • It is possible to feature engineer but for the scope of this project and time constraints, we will be dropping these features
      • Also, we can rely on CAMEO_INTL_2015 below to somewhat explain lifestages too
  • PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE, CAMEO_INTL_2015, PLZ8_BAUMAX - refer to detailed explanations below

def update_wohnlage(elem):
    if elem in [7, 8]:
        return 4
    elif elem == 0:
        return 3

def update_mixed(df):
    tmp = df.copy()
    # C - Remove mixed columns
    tmp.drop(['LP_LEBENSPHASE_FEIN', 'LP_LEBENSPHASE_GROB'], axis=1, inplace=True)
    # C.1 - PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE
    # Note: removed pd.to_datetime(df)
    tmp['defining_years'] = tmp['PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE'].apply(lambda x : PRAEGENDE_dict[x][0])
    tmp['mainstream_avantgarde'] = tmp['PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE'].apply(lambda x: PRAEGENDE_dict[x][1])
    # C.2 - CAMEO_INTL_2015
    tmp['CAMEO_INTL_2015'] = tmp['CAMEO_INTL_2015'].astype(float)
    tmp['wealth'] = tmp['CAMEO_INTL_2015'] // 10
    tmp['life_stage'] = tmp['CAMEO_INTL_2015'] % 10
    # C.3 - PLZ8_BAUMAX
    tmp['n_family_homes'] = tmp['PLZ8_BAUMAX'].apply(lambda x : 0 if x == 5 else x)
    tmp['family_or_business'] = tmp['PLZ8_BAUMAX'].apply(lambda x : 0 if x == 5 else 1)
    # C.4 - WOHNLAGE
    tmp['is_rural'] = tmp['WOHNLAGE'].apply(lambda x : 1 if x in [7, 8] else 0)
    tmp['neighborhood_score'] = tmp['WOHNLAGE'].apply(update_wohnlage)
    # Drop additional unnecessary columns above
    tmp.drop(['PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE', 'CAMEO_INTL_2015', 'PLZ8_BAUMAX', 'WOHNLAGE'], axis=1, inplace=True)
    return tmp

def clean_data(df):
    """
    Perform feature trimming, re-encoding, and engineering for demographics
    data
    
    INPUT: Demographics DataFrame
    OUTPUT: Trimmed and cleaned demographics DataFrame
    """
    tmp = df.copy()
    # convert missing value codes into NaNs, ...
    tmp = df_make_na(tmp)
    
    # Remove outlier columns
    tmp = tmp.drop(more_300k.index, axis=1)
    # remove rows with missing data
    sum_row_null = tmp.isnull().sum(axis=1)
    tmp = tmp[sum_row_null == 0]
    tmp.reset_index(inplace=True, drop=True)
    
    # select, re-encode, and engineer column values.
    # B.1 Drop columns
    tmp.drop(to_drop_categorical, axis=1, inplace=True)
    
    # B.2 East/West
    tmp['OST_WEST_KZ'] = tmp['OST_WEST_KZ'].map({'O' : 0, 'W' : 1})
    
    # B.3 Categorical columns to onehot encode
    res = pd.DataFrame()
    # transform, not fit_transform
    encoded_res = pd.DataFrame(one_hot.transform(tmp[['NATIONALITAET_KZ', 'SHOPPER_TYP']]).toarray())
    tmp = update_with_encoded(tmp, encoded_res, features=['NATIONALITAET_KZ', 'SHOPPER_TYP'])
    
    # C. Feature enginnering mixed
    tmp = update_mixed(tmp)
    
    # Label encode
    tmp['CAMEO_DEUG_2015'] = tmp['CAMEO_DEUG_2015'].astype(int)
    # Return the cleaned dataframe.
    return tmp

Discussion 2.1: Apply Feature Scaling¶

  • We are required to perform feature scaling due the following:
    1. We would be using Principal Component Analysis for feature importance analysis and dimensionality reduction
      • PCA is a variance maximizing exercise. It projects our original data onto directions which maximize the variance.
      • Hence, this is a distance-based measure, of which standardisation is required prior to fitting
    2. We are using a distance-based clustering algorithm, KMeans
      • Similarly as PCA, KMeans is sensitive to inputs, hence it needs to be scaled

Assumptions¶

  • It is important that our data are either numerical, interval
  • For categorical features, this can be applied for our ordinal features since we are assuming equal spacing by its labelling
  • Scaling would have no effects over binary features, so no problem here
  • We have made sure to either remove nominal categoricals or one-hot encode them, since it would make no sense to scale them

Step 2.2: Perform Dimensionality Reduction¶

On your scaled data, you are now ready to apply dimensionality reduction techniques.

  • Use sklearn's PCA class to apply principal component analysis on the data, thus finding the vectors of maximal variance in the data. To start, you should not set any parameters (so all components are computed) or set a number of components that is at least half the number of features (so there's enough features to see the general trend in variability).
  • Check out the ratio of variance explained by each principal component as well as the cumulative variance explained. Try plotting the cumulative or sequential values using matplotlib's plot() function. Based on what you find, select a value for the number of transformed features you'll retain for the clustering part of the project.
  • Once you've made a choice for the number of components to keep, make sure you re-fit a PCA instance to perform the decided-on transformation.

# Investigate the variance accounted for by each principal component.

def pca_scree(pca):
    variance = pca.explained_variance_ratio_
    n_pca=len(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)
    cum_variance = []
    x_labels = list(range(n_pca))
    for i in range(n_pca):
        if i == 0:
            cum_variance.append(variance[i])
        else:
            cum_variance.append(variance[i] + cum_variance[i - 1])
    plt.title('Explained variance per Principal Component (PC)')
    plt.xlabel('PC')
    plt.ylabel('Variance Explained (%)')
    plt.xticks(list(range(0, 85, 5)))
    plt.yticks([x / 10 for x in list(range(0, 11, 1))])
    plt.bar(x_labels, variance[:n_pca])
    plt.plot(x_labels, cum_variance[:n_pca], color='r')

  • 90% is well above these suggestions, n_components of 37 is chosen as it would hap to 90% of variation explained per scree plot

Step 2.3: Interpret Principal Components¶

Now that we have our transformed principal components, it's a nice idea to check out the weight of each variable on the first few components to see if they can be interpreted in some fashion.

As a reminder, each principal component is a unit vector that points in the direction of highest variance (after accounting for the variance captured by earlier principal components). The further a weight is from zero, the more the principal component is in the direction of the corresponding feature. If two features have large weights of the same sign (both positive or both negative), then increases in one tend expect to be associated with increases in the other. To contrast, features with different signs can be expected to show a negative correlation: increases in one variable should result in a decrease in the other.

  • To investigate the features, you should map each weight to their corresponding feature name, then sort the features according to weight. The most interesting features for each principal component, then, will be those at the beginning and end of the sorted list. Use the data dictionary document to help you understand these most prominent features, their relationships, and what a positive or negative value on the principal component might indicate.
  • You should investigate and interpret feature associations from the first three principal components in this substep. To help facilitate this, you should write a function that you can call at any time to print the sorted list of feature weights, for the i-th principal component. This might come in handy in the next step of the project, when you interpret the tendencies of the discovered clusters.

def pc_variance(pca, pc_num, num_limit=10):
    pc = pd.DataFrame({'attribute':columns, 'attribute_trans':columns_trans, 'score' : all_pca.components_[pc_num - 1]})
    pc_sorted = pc.sort_values(by='score', ascending=True)
    pc_filtered = pc_sorted.iloc[0:num_limit].append(pc_sorted.iloc[-num_limit:])
    pc_filtered.reset_index(inplace=True, drop=True)

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
    plt.yticks(pc_filtered.index, pc_filtered['attribute_trans'] + " - " + pc_filtered['attribute'])
    plt.barh(pc_filtered.index, pc_filtered['score'])
    plt.title(f'Top and under {num_limit} variance explained for Principal Component {pc_num}')
    plt.ylabel('Feature')
    plt.xlabel('Variance explained')
    plt.show()

  1. High density living - tend to have higher number of houses in the region (PLZ8_ANTG3, PLZ8_ANTG4), hence higher density of households (EWDICHTE)
  2. Lack of Money - higher 'wealth' score and household net income score (HH_EINKOMMEN_SCORE)
    • Note: the higher the score, the lower the wealth and net income

Negative correlations¶

  1. Movement - lower score (which is higher movement)
    • poorer households tend to move more frequently than other households, as they are more likely to experience negative mobility in the form of evictions and homeless episodes. Link.)
  2. Lower social status (LP_STATUS_FEIN)

PC2 - Measure of Older Generation¶

Positive correlations¶

  1. Estimated age given name analysis (ALTERSKATEGORIE_GROB) - older people with names of previous generations tend to be clumped together
  2. Less active or event oriented - Higher score equates to being less event oriented. Older people tend to be less active
  3. Less lustful (SEMIO_LUST) - Higher score equates to being less lustful. Older people tend to be less lust-ful than the younger generation

Negative correlations¶

  1. Less secular (more religious) - lower score of SEMIO_REL equates to being more religious
  2. Defining years - Older people tend to equate defining years to a much earlier period
  3. Less liberal (more conservative) - Elderly tend to have more conservative personalities, e.g. being dutiful (SEMIO_PFLICHT), traditional (SEMIO_TRADV) and appreciative of culture more (SEMIO_KULT). And financial more of a money saver (FINANZ_SPARER)

PC3 - Measure of Masculinity and emphasis over rationality¶

  • Note, a lower score in these typology surveys would mean the inverse

Positive and negative correlations¶

  1. Personalities - higher masculinity would mean having more of a combative attitude (SEMIO_KAEM), more dominant (SEMIO_DOM), a more rational person would be more critically-minded (SEMIO_KRIT) and rational (SEMIO_RAT)
    • the inverse can be observed for qualities for being dreamful (SEMIO_VERT), socially-minded (SEMIO_SOZ)
  2. Gender - These qualities are more often associated with males, hence gender being geared negatively in the graph (since our data plots 1 as male and 2 as female)
  3. Activities - Being more rational in day to day may equate to being more financially educated, hence a higher weight to being an investor (FINANZ_ANLEGER)
    • the inverse can be seen over low financial intesrest - FINANZ_MINIMALIST

Discussion 2.3: Interpret Principal Components¶

  • Based on our analysis above, it can be concluded that:
    1. PC1 is a measure of Poorness, with emphasis over money, living density, social status, and movement pattenrs
    2. PC2 is a measure of Elderly, with emphasis over age (given prevalence of name), defining years during youth, and personalities relating to being more liberal/convervative
    3. PC3 is a measure of Masculinity and Rationality, with emphasis over more masculine and rational personalities, and indirectly, financial habits. Unsurprisingly, this PC has a higher weightage to males than females.

Step 3.1: Apply Clustering to General Population¶

You've assessed and cleaned the demographics data, then scaled and transformed them. Now, it's time to see how the data clusters in the principal components space. In this substep, you will apply k-means clustering to the dataset and use the average within-cluster distances from each point to their assigned cluster's centroid to decide on a number of clusters to keep.

  • Use sklearn's KMeans class to perform k-means clustering on the PCA-transformed data.
  • Then, compute the average difference from each point to its assigned cluster's center. Hint: The KMeans object's .score() method might be useful here, but note that in sklearn, scores tend to be defined so that larger is better. Try applying it to a small, toy dataset, or use an internet search to help your understanding.

However, each additional cluster provides a smaller net benefit. Use this fact to select a final number of clusters in which to group the data. Warning: because of the large size of the dataset, it can take a long time for the algorithm to resolve. The more clusters to fit, the longer the algorithm will take. Step 3.3: Compare Customer Data to Demographics Data¶

At this point, you have clustered data based on demographics of the general population of Germany, and seen how the customer data for a mail-order sales company maps onto those demographic clusters. In this final substep, you will compare the two cluster distributions to see where the strongest customer base for the company is.

Consider the proportion of persons in each cluster for the general population, and the proportions for the customers. If we think the company's customer base to be universal, then the cluster assignment proportions should be fairly similar between the two. If there are only particular segments of the population that are interested in the company's products, then we should see a mismatch from one to the other. If there is a higher proportion of persons in a cluster for the customer data compared to the general population (e.g. 5% of persons are assigned to a cluster for the general population, but 15% of the customer data is closest to that cluster's centroid) then that suggests the people in that cluster to be a target audience for the company. On the other hand, the proportion of the data in a cluster being larger in the general population than the customer data (e.g. only 2% of customers closest to a population centroid that captures 6% of the data) suggests that group of persons to be outside of the target demographics.

Take a look at the following points in this step:

  • Compute the proportion of data points in each cluster for the general population and the customer data. Visualizations will be useful here: both for the individual dataset proportions, but also to visualize the ratios in cluster representation between groups. Seaborn's countplot() or barplot() function could be handy.
    • Recall the analysis you performed in step 1.1.3 of the project, where you separated out certain data points from the dataset if they had more than a specified threshold of missing values. If you found that this group was qualitatively different from the main bulk of the data, you should treat this as an additional data cluster in this analysis. Make sure that you account for the number of data points in this subset, for both the general population and customer datasets, when making your computations!
  • Which cluster or clusters are overrepresented in the customer dataset compared to the general population? Select at least one such cluster and infer what kind of people might be represented by that cluster. Use the principal component interpretations from step 2.3 or look at additional components to help you make this inference. Alternatively, you can use the .inverse_transform() method of the PCA and StandardScaler objects to transform centroids back to the original data space and interpret the retrieved values directly.
  • Perform a similar investigation for the underrepresented clusters. Which cluster or clusters are underrepresented in the customer dataset compared to the general population, and what kinds of people are typified by these clusters?

def cluster_feature_importances(cluster_index, cluster_centroid):

    plt.xlabel('Principal component')
    plt.bar(label_lst, cluster_centroid[cluster_index])
    plt.show()
